s (category, freshness_rule_config) pairs to the TTL calculation function and verify the returned TTL matches expected values. Test different data types (user profiles, product catalog, etc.) with their configured rules. Include edge cases like zero TTL or infinite TTL.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior requires observing cache behavior under memory pressure. A pure logic test with mocked memory checks would miss real failures in how the cache calculates its own memory usage or how the strategy-switching integrates with cache operations. The real failure could be: (1) strategy-switching logic is wrong (Unit catches), or (2) memory pressure isn't correctly detected in the actual cache implementation (Integration/System catches). Integration level—actually filling a cache and triggering memory-pressure conditions—catches both. Mocking memory without actually exercising the cache would hide real integration bugs.","test_description":"Create a cache with LRU strategy and set a low memory threshold. Incrementally add items until memory usage exceeds the threshold. Verify the eviction strategy changes to LFU. Test with multiple thresholds and verify the switch is idempotent (switching twice doesn't cause errors).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior spans two systems: the cache and the database. The real failure is not just in the invalidation logic, but in whether invalidation is actually triggered when the database is written. If invalidation is triggered by a database trigger, ORM hook, or event listener, we must write to an actual database to test it. A unit test that mocks DB writes at the ORM level would miss failures in the database-side trigger mechanism, event subscription, or timing. Integration level with a local test database catches the full flow.","test_description":"Use a test PostgreSQL database. Insert/update/delete rows in a table that has cached entries. Verify that cache keys corresponding to the affected rows are invalidated. Test multiple operations in sequence and verify only relevant cache entries are invalidated (not over-invalidation). Verify invalidation happens synchronously or with acceptable latency.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure eviction algorithm logic. Given a cache state with known access patterns (timestamps for LRU, frequencies for LFU), the algorithm must return the correct entry to evict. The failure is in the comparison or data structure (e.g., wrong comparison operator, forgot to track frequency). This can be tested entirely in-process by creating a cache object, controlling access patterns programmatically, and verifying which entry is selected for eviction.","test_description":"Create in-memory cache objects with LRU and LFU strategies. Add entries with known access timestamps/frequencies. Fill cache beyond capacity. Verify eviction removes the least-recently-used entry (LRU) or least-frequently-used entry (LFU) respectively. Test tie-breaking (when multiple entries have same recency/frequency).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.02,"Agentic